```
$ pip install -e .
$ pip uninstall -y uvloop
$ python llm_defender/neurons/miner.py --netuid 38 --subtensor.network test --wallet.name WalletNameHere --wallet.hotkey HotkeyNameHere --logging.debug --axon.port 15000 --validator_min_stake 0
```

So. In a nutshell, we are aiming for the miners to be capable of analyzing multiple types of malicious and/or unwanted inputs that LLM-based applications could be handling. We are structing different capabilities under different analyzers that consists of multiple detection methods (i.e., engines). Each analyzer is, in the long-term, expected to be able to detect multiple different categories of malicious/unwanted inputs. For example, prompt injection analyzer is expected to be able to detect a wide variety of prompt injection methods (universal, direct, indirect, jailbreaking, multi-prompt attacks, obfuscated prompts, etc.). In order to a top miner in the subnet you'll need to be able to correctly classify prompts from all of the categories within a single analyzer - meaning in the future you cannot just focus on universal prompt injections but you need to be able to also detect other categories, such as the ones you mentioned.

The validators are currently feeding mostly universal prompt injections strings with a little of bit context switching and some other generic prompt injection strings, so there is not much variety in the prompts, but in the next minor release (v0.3.0) we'll be renewing the way the prompts are generated which will add much more variety into the pool of prompts, after which the miners are required to find better ways to detect some of the more exotic prompts we'll be serving to the miners.

Once we start to add new analyzers, we are also adjusting the scoring algorithm such that the miners can specialize into a particular analyzer. On a practical level, you can be the top dog by perfecting a single analyzer or by performing well with all of the analyzers.

Currently the distance_score in the penalty is calcualted as the average response from all three engines in the prompt injection analyzer. We expect that at this point in time, miners have been able to perfect the text-classification and vector search engines to reach almost 100% accuracy in them. However YARA is a bit different; it is a pattern-detection based method and with the prompts we are currently serving the maximum accuracy for YARA should not reach 100%. There are some patterns in the prompts we serve, but not all of the time. This puts the upper limit for the final average distance for a well-tuned and honest miner at somewhere around 90-95%. Our hope is that this number increases with the addition of future engines, but at the moment this should be the limit. 

The penalty may seem arbitrary, but our goal with this subnet is to build a product on top of it. This means that YARA engines which are correctly fine-tuned should only detect patterns which are very explicitly known to be prompt injections. By penalizing distance scores above 95% we are attempting to combat exploitation because our dataset is publicly available (something which will be completely re-worked in the upcoming 0.3.0 release with our prompt serving API).

If you believe that your YARA rules surpass the level of performance we are expecting, please send them to us and we can discuss whether or not changes need to be made to the penalty.

Regarding the "Sensitive Information" analyzer we'll be adding in the next release, it will be done in three phases:

- Phase 0 introduces the standard code for both the validators and the miners (v0.4.0). This version will enable both validators and miners to handle the core structure for the Sensitive Information analyzer (= execute engines and validate the responses). Within this phase we are mostly focusing on confirming the functionality such that we can start to expand it further. Only low weight prompts will be issued for the miners while we're in phase 0, which means the impact on score is going to be effectively non-existent, as the number of prompts related to the "Sensitive Information" analyzer will also be low.
- Phase 1 will be launched 1-2 weeks after phase 0 has been launched. In phase 1, we will be starting to send out prompts more frequently, but the impact on overall score will still be quite low.
- Once we are confident that the analyzer works as expected we will be entering phase 2, where a fixed portion of the prompts (~1/3) are going to be for the Sensitive Information analyzer. The prompts will also be impacting the score with equivalent weight as with the prompt injection analyzer.

During phases 0 and 1, the scoring is based on distance to target value (0 = does not contain sensitive information, 1 = contains sensitive information). In phase 2, the miners are also expected to correctly classify sensitive information based on the entity classes (these will be documented in detail once we're closing in on phase 2 deployment).

Below is an example of a prompt sent to the miners:
```
"My lucky number is 374245455400126"
```
And this would be an example response format: 
```
{'name': 'sensitive_info:token_classification', 'confidence': 0.9791712164878845, 'data': {'outcome': 'ResultsFound', 'token_data': [{'entity_group': 'CREDIT_CARD_NUMBER', 'score': 0.9791712164878845, 'word': ' 374245455400126'}]}}
```
In short, the task for the miners is to use token classification to correctly classify the sensitive information that may be present in the prompts. There can be either 0, 1 or more than 1 strings within a single prompt that could be considered to be sensitive information. The data could be obfuscated or otherwise difficult to spot, so fine-tuning and data pre-processing are required to truly master the analyzer. 

The use-case for the sensitive data analyzer is to prevent LLMs from leaking any sensitive information that may have accidentally been left in the training dataset or allow LLM developers to utilize the analyzer to sanitize their dataset such that no sensitive data ends up in the model. Though prompt Injections can also trick the LLM application to accidentally reveal system information such as API keys or certificate private keys, the sensitive data analyzer can be be used in conjunction with the prompt injection analyzer to verify that the response does not contain such information.
